### Goroutines

A goroutine is a lightweight thread managed by the Go runtime.

### Starting a Goroutine

Use the `go` keyword to start a goroutine:

```go
func sayHello() {
    fmt.Println("Hello from goroutine!")
}

func main() {
    go sayHello()
    time.Sleep(time.Millisecond) // wait for goroutine
}
```

### Anonymous Goroutines

```go
func main() {
    go func() {
        fmt.Println("Anonymous goroutine")
    }()
    time.Sleep(time.Millisecond)
}
```

### Goroutines are Lightweight

- Stack starts at 2KB (vs ~1MB for OS threads)
- Goroutines are multiplexed onto OS threads
- Thousands of goroutines are practical

```go
func main() {
    var wg sync.WaitGroup
    for i := 0; i < 1000; i++ {
        wg.Add(1)
        go func(id int) {
            defer wg.Done()
            fmt.Println("goroutine", id)
        }(i)
    }
    wg.Wait()
}
```

### Goroutine Scheduling

- Go uses M:N scheduling (M goroutines on N OS threads)
- `GOMAXPROCS` controls the number of OS threads
- Default: number of CPU cores

```go
import "runtime"
fmt.Println("CPUs:", runtime.NumCPU())
fmt.Println("GOMAXPROCS:", runtime.GOMAXPROCS(0))
```

### Main Goroutine

The `main()` function itself runs as a goroutine. When `main()` returns, all goroutines are terminated.

```go
func main() {
    go func() {
        fmt.Println("This may not print")
    }()
    // main returns, program exits
}
```

Use synchronization (WaitGroup, channels) to ensure goroutines complete.

> **Key Point:** Goroutines are not OS threads - they are cooperatively scheduled by the Go runtime and are very cheap to create. Always use synchronization to wait for goroutines.

codeExample:
package main

import (
    "fmt"
    "sync"
)

func worker(id int, wg *sync.WaitGroup) {
    defer wg.Done()
    fmt.Printf("Worker %d starting\n", id)
    fmt.Printf("Worker %d done\n", id)
}

func main() {
    var wg sync.WaitGroup

    for i := 1; i <= 5; i++ {
        wg.Add(1)
        go worker(i, &wg)
    }

    wg.Wait()
    fmt.Println("All workers completed")
}
